ze:12pt">, the person in the more powerful vehicle is automatically presumed to be at fault </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">a road traffic collision. This presumption can</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, however, </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">be rebutted in the face of evidence to the contrary. By </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">shifting the onus </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">to the driver </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">encourage</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> m</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">otorists </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">aware of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">cyclists. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> public awareness campaign would need to be brought in on the introduction of strict liability</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> to support this message</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. This would have the joint aim of educating road users and mitigating any negative publicity that</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> may be gene</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">rated by the introduction of strict liability</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-siz